SIMPLE: melody
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Melody
<hw>Mel"o*dy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Melodies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>melodie</ets>, F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧lodie</ets>, L. <ets>melodia</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ a singing,
choral song, fr. <?/ musical, melodious; <grk>me`los</grk> song, tune +
<?/ song. See <er>Ode</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A sweet or agreeable succession of sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lulled with sound of sweetest <qex>melody</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A rhythmical succession of single
tones, ranging for the most part within a given key, and so related
together as to form a musical whole, having the unity of what is
technically called a musical thought, at once pleasing to the ear and
characteristic in expression.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Melody</xex> consists in a succession of single
tones; <xex>harmony</xex> is a consonance or agreement of tones, also a
succession of consonant musical combinations or chords.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The air or tune of a musical piece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Harmony</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meloe</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
